For example, you could look at a pile of 180 copper coins, and you would learn that it held about 200 coins, but you couldn't determine there were exactly 180 coins.
The type of object you name can be as specific or general as you like—"dented copper coins" is as viable as "coins"—but the distinguishing features must be obvious at a glance, and the spell is automatically fooled objects disguised as other objects. For instance, the spell would register copper coins plated in gold as gold coins, not copper coins.
